00:20:42,810 --> 00:20:44,930
<font color="#ff00ff">(GRUNTS, PANTING)</font>

249
00:20:47,850 --> 00:20:50,640
<font color="#ff00ff">(DOOR CREAKING)</font>

250
00:21:01,430 --> 00:21:04,430
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

251
00:21:13,850 --> 00:21:16,010
<font color="#ff00ff">(GRUNTS)</font>

252
00:21:16,020 --> 00:21:17,620
Let's go!

253
00:21:17,680 --> 00:21:19,020
Let's go!

254
00:21:20,300 --> 00:21:21,750
Hey!

255
00:21:21,760 --> 00:21:23,340
<font color="#ff00ff">(GASPS)</font>

256
00:21:26,520 --> 00:21:28,640
<font color="#ff00ff">(GROANS)</font>

257
00:21:28,640 --> 00:21:29,890
Hey!

258
00:21:29,890 --> 00:21:32,020
<font color="#ff00ff">(ALARM BUZZING)</font>

259
00:21:34,890 --> 00:21:37,350
<font color="#ff00ff">(PANTING)</font>

260
00:21:41,350 --> 00:21:43,470
<font color="#ff00ff">(PEOPLE CHATTERING)</font>

261
00:21:45,520 --> 00:21:48,350
<font color="#ff00ff">(DISTANT SIRENS WAILING)</font>

262
00:21:50,350 --> 00:21:52,720
<font color="#138ce9">WOMAN:</font> Lyudmilla! Do
you want to come with us?

263
00:21:52,730 --> 00:21:53,940
Come where?

264
00:21:53,940 --> 00:21:56,260
We're going to the railroad
bridge to get a better look.

265
00:21:56,270 --> 00:21:58,720
It's not like anyone can
sleep with all the sirens.

266
00:21:58,730 --> 00:22:01,120
I don't think you should
go. It could be dangerous.

267
00:22:01,120 --> 00:22:04,220
What do you mean dangerous? It's a
fire. It's over there, we're over here.

268
00:22:04,220 --> 00:22:05,850
- Mikhail.
- What?

269
00:22:07,230 --> 00:22:09,270
Oh, sorry.

270
00:22:09,270 --> 00:22:10,850
Oh.

271
00:22:13,730 --> 00:22:16,390
- <font color="#138ce9">OKSANA:</font> Is Vasily...?
- Yeah.

272
00:22:16,390 --> 00:22:18,060
Did he say it was bad?

273
00:22:18,060 --> 00:22:19,890
No. No, he said it was just the roof.

274
00:22:19,900 --> 00:22:21,470
Well, he's never gotten hurt before.

275
00:22:21,470 --> 00:22:23,100
None of the boys have.

276
00:22:24,030 --> 00:22:25,690
He'll be fine.

277
00:22:27,180 --> 00:22:28,560
Get some rest.

278
00:22:32,220 --> 00:22:34,390
<font color="#ff00ff">(DISTANT SIRENS CONTINUING)</font>

279
00:22:40,060 --> 00:22:42,100
<font color="#138ce9">DYATLOV:</font> The tank, it's big enough.

280
00:22:42,100 --> 00:22:46,430
This kind of explosion, the control
tank on 71, it's 100 cubic meters.

281
00:22:46,430 --> 00:22:47,850
One hundred and ten.

282
00:22:47,850 --> 00:22:50,680
Hundred and ten. It
could do this, definitely.

283
00:22:50,680 --> 00:22:54,100
<font color="#ff00ff">(PANTING)</font>:{\c} It's gone.

284
00:22:54,100 --> 00:22:56,260
I looked right into it.

285
00:22:56,270 --> 00:22:57,970
I looked into the core.

286
00:22:59,100 --> 00:23:01,930
Did you lower the control rods or not?

287
00:23:01,930 --> 00:23:04,390
<font color="#ff00ff">(RETCHING)</font>

288
00:23:04,390 --> 00:23:06,770
Take him to the infirmary.

289
00:23:08,270 --> 00:23:09,970
Toptunov, take him!

290
00:23:13,390 --> 00:23:17,180
- Where's Kudryavstev?
- He fell.

291
00:23:17,180 --> 00:23:20,310
- <font color="#138ce9">TOPTUNOV:</font> I need a medic! Anyone!
- He's delusional.

292
00:23:20,310 --> 00:23:22,810
- His face...
- Ruptured condenser lines.

293
00:23:22,810 --> 00:23:24,810
The feedwater is mildly contaminated.

294
00:23:24,810 --> 00:23:26,560
He'll be fine. I've seen worse.

295
00:23:26,560 --> 00:23:28,970
Do we still have a phone
line to the outside?

296
00:23:30,810 --> 00:23:33,600
- Akimov?
- <font color="#ff00ff">(GRUNTS)</font>

297
00:23:33,600 --> 00:23:35,640
Call in the day shift.

298
00:23:36,850 --> 00:23:39,470
- But if the...
- We have to keep water flowing into the core.

299
00:23:39,470 --> 00:23:42,640
We need electricians,
mechanics, we need bodies.

300
00:23:43,430 --> 00:23:46,020
How many times do I have to say it?

301
00:23:53,930 --> 00:23:56,180
I'm going to the
Administration Building now

302
00:23:56,180 --> 00:23:58,810
to call Bryukhanov and Fomin.

303
00:23:58,810 --> 00:24:01,220
They're gonna want a full report.

304
00:24:02,270 --> 00:24:06,180
Now, I don't know if I can
make things better for you,

305
00:24:06,180 --> 00:24:09,020
but I can certainly make them worse.

306
00:24:11,020 --> 00:24:13,640
Call in the day shift, Comrade Akimov.

307
00:24:17,040 --> 00:24:18,710
Yes, Comrade Dyatlov.

308
00:24:27,350 --> 00:24:29,310
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIGHS)</font>

309
00:24:31,970 --> 00:24:33,310
<font color="#ff00ff">(DOOR CLOSES)</font>

310
00:24:51,560 --> 00:24:54,360
- <font color="#ff00ff">(WOMAN MOANS SOFTLY)</font>
- You're doing fine.

311
00:24:54,370 --> 00:24:56,280
Raise her up.

312
00:24:59,640 --> 00:25:01,390
That one, maybe an hour.

313
00:25:01,390 --> 00:25:03,560
This one, not until morning.

314
00:25:05,640 --> 00:25:09,680
- How's it downstairs, doctor?
- Quiet.

315
00:25:09,680 --> 00:25:11,470
Always is.

316
00:25:11,470 --> 00:25:14,220
Nothing at this hour but babies.

317
00:25:15,100 --> 00:25:18,060
You know, I once went
two days without sleep?

318
00:25:18,060 --> 00:25:20,760
Ten women went into
labor at the same time.

319
00:25:20,770 --> 00:25:23,140
- Did I ever tell you that story?
- Yes.

320
00:25:25,270 --> 00:25:27,100
Well, I won't need you
in here for a while.

321
00:25:27,100 --> 00:25:29,890
If you want, get some
rest in the break room.

322
00:25:30,770 --> 00:25:33,010
They haven't brought
anyone in from the fire.

323
00:25:33,020 --> 00:25:36,100
- What fire?
- The power plant.

324
00:25:36,770 --> 00:25:39,770
Oh. Then it mustn't be too bad.

325
00:25:40,840 --> 00:25:42,670
Do we stock iodine?

326
00:25:42,670 --> 00:25:44,590
- Hmm?
- Iodine.

327
00:25:45,930 --> 00:25:47,320
You mean disinfectant?

328
00:25:47,320 --> 00:25:50,140
No, pills. Does the
hospital stock iodine pills?

329
00:25:50,140 --> 00:25:53,100
Iodine pills? Why would
we have iodine pills?

330
00:25:53,810 --> 00:25:55,930
<font color="#ff00ff">(PHONE RINGS)</font>

331
00:25:58,770 --> 00:26:00,810
<font color="#ff00ff">(PHONE RINGS)</font>

332
00:26:03,890 --> 00:26:05,310
<font color="#ff00ff">(PHONE RINGS)</font>

333
00:26:05,310 --> 00:26:07,600
Hello? <font color="#ff00ff">(COUGHING)</font>

334
00:26:08,680 --> 00:26:10,100
Hello?

335
00:26:17,070 --> 00:26:18,950
Who else knows this?

336
00:26:21,020 --> 00:26:22,680
Have you called Fomin?

337
00:26:23,970 --> 00:26:25,970
Of course I want you to call him.

338
00:26:25,970 --> 00:26:28,180
If I'm up, he's up.

339
00:26:30,810 --> 00:26:33,600
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

340
00:26:51,220 --> 00:26:53,640
<font color="#ff00ff">(SIRENS WAILING)</font>

341
00:27:06,390 --> 00:27:08,510
<font color="#138ce9">FOMIN:</font> Whatever the cause,
the important thing is

342
00:27:08,520 --> 00:27:10,220
that neither you nor I...

343
00:27:30,890 --> 00:27:32,930
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

344
00:27:44,600 --> 00:27:47,100
<font color="#ff00ff">(HEAVY DOOR THUDDING)</font>

345
00:27:51,350 --> 00:27:53,430
I take it the safety test was a failure?

346
00:27:53,430 --> 00:27:56,760
- We have the situation under control.
- <font color="#138ce9">FOMIN:</font> Under control?

347
00:27:56,770 --> 00:27:59,560
- It doesn't look like it's under control.
- Shut up, Fomin.

348
00:28:00,890 --> 00:28:03,790
I have to tell the Central Committee
about this. Do you realize that?

349
00:28:03,790 --> 00:28:05,970
I have to get on the
phone and tell Maryin,

350
00:28:05,970 --> 00:28:07,510
or God forbid Frolyshev,

351
00:28:07,520 --> 00:28:09,310
that my power plant is on fire.

352
00:28:09,310 --> 00:28:11,810
No one can blame you for
this, Director Bryukhanov.

353
00:28:11,810 --> 00:28:13,600
Of course no one can blame me for this.

354
00:28:13,600 --> 00:28:16,770
How can I be responsible?
I was sleeping.

355
00:28:17,600 --> 00:28:19,930
Tell me what happened, quickly.

356
00:28:21,390 --> 00:28:25,180
We ran the test exactly as
Chief Engineer Fomin approved.

357
00:28:25,180 --> 00:28:28,160
Unit Shift Chief Akimov
and Engineer Toptunov

358
00:28:28,160 --> 00:28:30,170
encountered technical
difficulties leading

359
00:28:30,170 --> 00:28:33,850
to an accumulation of hydrogen
in the control system tank.

360
00:28:33,850 --> 00:28:35,470
It regrettably ignited,

361
00:28:35,470 --> 00:28:38,100
damaging the plant,
setting the roof on fire.

362
00:28:40,350 --> 00:28:42,310
The tank is quite large.

363
00:28:42,310 --> 00:28:44,430
It's the only logical explanation.

364
00:28:44,430 --> 00:28:47,970
Of course, Deputy Chief Engineer Dyatlov

365
00:28:47,970 --> 00:28:50,680
was directly supervising the test,

366
00:28:50,680 --> 00:28:52,040
so he would know best.

367
00:28:52,050 --> 00:28:54,470
- <font color="#138ce9">BRYUKHANOV:</font> A hydrogen tank, fire...
- <font color="#ff00ff">(PEN SCRIBBLING)</font>

368
00:28:56,520 --> 00:28:58,640
- Reactor?
- We're taking measures to ensure

369
00:28:58,640 --> 00:29:01,140
a steady flow of water through the core.

370
00:29:01,140 --> 00:29:04,180
- What about radiation?
- Obviously, down here it's nothing.

371
00:29:04,180 --> 00:29:06,970
But in the reactor
building, I'm being told

372
00:29:06,970 --> 00:29:09,100
3.6 roentgen per hour.

373
00:29:09,100 --> 00:29:11,350
Well, that's not great,
but it's not horrifying.

374
00:29:11,350 --> 00:29:13,010
Not at all.

375
00:29:13,020 --> 00:29:16,140
- From the feedwater, I assume?
- Mm-hmm.

376
00:29:16,140 --> 00:29:18,510
We'll have to limit shifts

377
00:29:18,520 --> 00:29:20,680
to six hours at a time, but otherwise...

378
00:29:20,680 --> 00:29:23,270
The dosimetrists should
be checking regularly.

379
00:29:24,140 --> 00:29:28,060
Have them use the good
meter from the safe.

380
00:29:29,060 --> 00:29:32,230
Right. I'll call Maryin.

381
00:29:33,270 --> 00:29:35,600
Have them wake up the
local executive committee.

382
00:29:35,600 --> 00:29:37,850
There'll be orders coming down.

383
00:29:37,850 --> 00:29:40,890
<font color="#ff00ff">(CROWD MURMURING)</font>

384
00:29:43,520 --> 00:29:45,060
- Here.
- <font color="#ff00ff">(WHISPERS)</font>:{\c} No.

385
00:29:45,060 --> 00:29:47,680
You sure? Okay.

386
00:29:50,680 --> 00:29:53,350
- What do you think makes the colors?
- Oh...

387
00:29:54,020 --> 00:29:57,470
- It's the fuel for sure.
- "Oh. It's the fuel for sure"?

388
00:29:57,470 --> 00:30:00,970
What do you know about it? You
clean floors at a train station.

389
00:30:00,970 --> 00:30:02,760
My friend, Yuri, works
at the power plant.

390
00:30:02,770 --> 00:30:04,430
He says it runs cold.

391
00:30:04,430 --> 00:30:06,620
No gas, no fire. Just atoms.

392
00:30:06,620 --> 00:30:09,730
Yuri says the only thing is, you
can't walk right up to the fuel.

393
00:30:09,730 --> 00:30:12,510
If you do, a glass of vodka
an hour for four hours.

394
00:30:12,520 --> 00:30:15,510
<font color="#ff00ff">(LAUGHS)</font> Isn't Yuri a plumber?

395
00:30:15,520 --> 00:30:17,930
At the nuclear power plant, yeah.

396
00:30:24,470 --> 00:30:26,060
It is beautiful.

397
00:30:27,100 --> 00:30:28,730
Yeah.

398
00:30:30,890 --> 00:30:32,930
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

399
00:30:35,970 --> 00:30:39,350
<font color="#ff00ff">(WIND BLOWING SOFTLY)</font>

400
00:30:53,600 --> 00:30:55,970
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

401
00:31:26,770 --> 00:31:28,810
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

402
00:31:39,350 --> 00:31:41,470
<font color="#ff00ff">(DISTANT ALARM WAILING)</font>

403
00:31:44,970 --> 00:31:46,930
<font color="#ff00ff">(COUGHING)</font>

404
00:32:20,170 --> 00:32:22,170
Do you have a cigarette?

405
00:32:47,640 --> 00:32:49,640
Do you need help?

406
00:32:55,640 --> 00:32:57,730
It's over.

407
00:32:59,890 --> 00:33:02,060
<font color="#ff00ff">(DISTANT SIRENS CONTINUING)</font>

408
00:33:17,220 --> 00:33:20,390
<font color="#ff00ff">(TRICKLING, PATTERING)</font>

409
00:33:35,220 --> 00:33:37,730
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

410
00:33:49,470 --> 00:33:51,730
<font color="#ff00ff">(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)</font>

411
00:34:01,790 --> 00:34:03,600
We've done all we can
from the perimeter.

412
00:34:03,600 --> 00:34:06,430
We need to start making
our way to the roof.

413
00:34:12,430 --> 00:34:15,770
Vasily! You've gotta put it out.

414
00:34:19,140 --> 00:34:22,180
<font color="#138ce9">PRAVIK:</font> That's enough,
comrades. We're pushing ahead.

415
00:34:28,100 --> 00:34:29,720
<font color="#138ce9">PRAVIK:</font> Come on, boys.

416
00:34:35,600 --> 00:34:37,560
Vasily, it's just past, straight up.

417
00:34:37,560 --> 00:34:39,470
All the way up, all the way in.

418
00:34:41,520 --> 00:34:43,020
Come on!

419
00:34:46,640 --> 00:34:48,680
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

420
00:34:55,140 --> 00:34:57,310
<font color="#138ce9">FIREMAN:</font> Yeah. Going in now.

421
00:35:15,890 --> 00:35:19,180
<font color="#ffff00">♪ </font><font color="#ffff00">♪</font>

422
00:35:38,100 --> 00:35:40,310
<font color="#ff00ff">(DISTANT ALARMS BLARING, BUZZING)</font>

423
00:35:44,470 --> 00:35:46,810
What about the auxiliary?

424
00:35:46,810 --> 00:35:50,310
The pumps are gone, electrical's gone.

425
00:35:50,310 --> 00:35:54,220
- The core?
- I didn't go in there, and I won't.

426
00:35:55,610 --> 00:35:58,560
- I think it's time we faced...
- No, we have to get water into the core.

427
00:35:58,560 --> 00:36:00,390
Otherwise, there'll be a meltdown.

428
00:36:00,390 --> 00:36:02,390
We have to open the valves.

429
00:36:02,390 --> 00:36:04,500
- Sasha...
- What do you want, Boris?

430
00:36:04,510 --> 00:36:06,560
If it's true, then we're dead,
a million people are dead.

431
00:36:06,560 --> 00:36:08,730
Is that what you need to hear?

432
00:36:10,180 --> 00:36:12,220
We have to open the valves.

433
00:36:12,220 --> 00:36:14,430
- By hand.
- By hand?

434
00:36:14,430 --> 00:36:17,060
You know, the number of valves,
the amount of time to turn them,

435
00:36:17,060 --> 00:36:18,760
you're talking about hours in there!

436
00:36:18,770 --> 00:36:20,560
- Then help us.
- Help you do what?

437
00:36:20,570 --> 00:36:23,730
Pump water into a ditch?
There's nothing there!

438
00:36:32,930 --> 00:36:34,890
Leonid, I'm begging you.

439
00:36:48,270 --> 00:36:50,010
Watch the panel while we're gone.

440
00:36:50,020 --> 00:36:51,470
It's not working.

441
00:36:52,560 --> 00:36:54,390
Just watch it.

442
00:36:59,150 --> 00:37:00,770
<font color="#ff00ff">(DOOR CLOSES)</font>

443
00:37:11,850 --> 00:37:13,310
<font color="#ff00ff">(CRYING)</font>

444
00:37:13,310 --> 00:37:16,060
<font color="#ff00ff">(DISTANT SIRENS WAILING)</font>

445
00:37:16,060 --> 00:37:18,230
<font color="#138ce9">WORKER:</font> I guess we know
why they called us in early.

446
00:37:18,230 --> 00:37:20,640
<font color="#138ce9">SITNIKOV:</font> Is anyone
saying what happened?

447
00:37:20,640 --> 00:37:22,970
<font color="#138ce9">WORKER:</font> They were running the
safety test on the turbines,

448
00:37:22,970 --> 00:37:25,100
blew the control system tank.

449
00:37:26,220 --> 00:37:27,640
It doesn't make sense to me either.

450
00:37:29,240 --> 00:37:31,450
What about sabotage?

451
00:37:31,450 --> 00:37:32,990
A bomb?

452
00:37:34,020 --> 00:37:37,560
Sitnikov! Bryukhanov wants
us to use the good dosimeter,

453
00:37:37,560 --> 00:37:40,430
but it's in the safe,
and we can't find the key.

454
00:37:40,430 --> 00:37:43,850
It's in Building 2. Hasn't...?

455
00:37:43,850 --> 00:37:45,520
Follow me.

456
00:37:47,430 --> 00:37:49,390
<font color="#ff00ff">(DOOR OPENS)</font>

457
00:37:56,930 --> 00:37:58,510
Gentlemen, welcome.

458
00:37:58,520 --> 00:38:01,760
Please, uh, find a seat. Plenty of room.

459
00:38:01,770 --> 00:38:05,350
I apologize for the
lateness of the hour.

460
00:38:05,350 --> 00:38:09,510
Rest assured, we are
all very safe down here.

461
00:38:09,520 --> 00:38:12,260
We built this shelter to
withstand a nuclear attack

462
00:38:12,270 --> 00:38:15,560
by the Americans, so
I think we'll be fine.

463
00:38:17,270 --> 00:38:19,680
As you can see, we have
experienced an accident.

464
00:38:19,680 --> 00:38:22,350
A large control tank malfunctioned,

465
00:38:22,350 --> 00:38:26,310
damaging reactor Building
4 and starting a fire.

466
00:38:26,310 --> 00:38:30,060
Now, I have spoken directly
to Deputy Secretary Maryin.

467
00:38:30,060 --> 00:38:32,390
Maryin spoke to Deputy Chief Frolyshev,

468
00:38:32,390 --> 00:38:35,680
Frolyshev to Central
Committee member Dolgikh,

469
00:38:35,680 --> 00:38:39,200
and Dolgikh to General
Secretary Gorbachev.

470
00:38:39,210 --> 00:38:40,970
Now...

471
00:38:40,970 --> 00:38:46,310
Because the Central Committee
has the greatest respect

472
00:38:46,310 --> 00:38:50,350
for the work of the
Pripyat Executive Committee,

473
00:38:50,350 --> 00:38:54,350
they have asked me to brief you
on matters as they stand, so...

474
00:38:55,890 --> 00:38:59,720
First, the accident...
<font color="#ff00ff">(STAMMERS)</font> is well under control.

475
00:38:59,730 --> 00:39:05,060
And second, because the efforts
of the Soviet nuclear industry

476
00:39:05,060 --> 00:39:08,850
are considered key state
secrets, it is important

477
00:39:08,850 --> 00:39:12,260
that we ensure that this incident

478
00:39:12,270 --> 00:39:14,430
has no adverse consequences.

479
00:39:14,430 --> 00:39:18,640
Now, to prevent a panic, the
Central Committee have ordered

480
00:39:18,640 --> 00:39:21,600
a detachment of military
police to Pripyat.

481
00:39:21,600 --> 00:39:23,430
How large of a detachment?

482
00:39:24,850 --> 00:39:26,970
Between two and four thousand men.

483
00:39:26,970 --> 00:39:29,100
<font color="#ff00ff">(MURMURING)</font>

484
00:39:29,100 --> 00:39:33,010
What's really going on
here? How dangerous is this?

485
00:39:33,020 --> 00:39:37,100
There's mild radiation, but
it's limited to the plant itself.

486
00:39:37,100 --> 00:39:40,260
- <font color="#138ce9">PETROV:</font> No, it isn't.
- Excuse me?

487
00:39:40,270 --> 00:39:44,260
You saw men outside vomiting.

488
00:39:44,270 --> 00:39:46,100
You saw men with burns.

489
00:39:47,180 --> 00:39:49,640
There's more radiation
than they're saying.

490
00:39:49,640 --> 00:39:52,010
We have wives here, we have children.

491
00:39:52,020 --> 00:39:54,810
I say we evacuate the town.

492
00:39:54,810 --> 00:39:56,640
<font color="#138ce9">BRYUKHANOV:</font> Gentlemen...

493
00:39:56,640 --> 00:40:00,800
Please, please. My wife is here.

494
00:40:00,810 --> 00:40:02,930
Do you think I would keep her in Pripyat

495
00:40:02,930 --> 00:40:04,470
if it wasn't safe?

496
00:40:04,470 --> 00:40:08,180
Bryukhanov, the air is glowing.

497
00:40:08,180 --> 00:40:11,390
The Cherenkov effect.
Completely normal phenomenon.

498
00:40:11,400 --> 00:40:13,260
It can happen with minimal radiation.

499
00:40:13,270 --> 00:40:17,810
- <font color="#ff00ff">(MURMURING)</font>
- <font color="#ff00ff">(LOUD TAPPING)</font>

500
00:40:17,820 --> 00:40:19,980
<font color="#ff00ff">(MURMURING STOPS)</font>

501
00:40:23,600 --> 00:40:27,640
I wonder how many of you
know the name of this place.

502
00:40:29,810 --> 00:40:33,470
We all call it "Chernobyl," of course.

503
00:40:33,470 --> 00:40:35,810
What is its real name?

504
00:40:37,270 --> 00:40:40,930
The Vladimir I. Lenin
Nuclear Power Station.

505
00:40:40,930 --> 00:40:42,850
Exactly.

506
00:40:44,970 --> 00:40:48,850
Vladimir I. Lenin.

507
00:40:55,970 --> 00:40:59,680
And how proud he would
be of you all tonight.

508
00:41:00,730 --> 00:41:03,020
Especially you, young man,

509
00:41:04,020 --> 00:41:06,890
and the passion you have for the people.

510
00:41:07,680 --> 00:41:11,890
For is that not the sole purpose
of the apparatus of the State?

511
00:41:13,560 --> 00:41:15,640
Sometimes, we forget.

512
00:41:16,850 --> 00:41:19,520
Sometimes, we fall prey to fear.

513
00:41:21,140 --> 00:41:25,010
But our faith in Soviet socialism

514
00:41:25,020 --> 00:41:27,930
will always be rewarded.

515
00:41:30,350 --> 00:41:34,680
Now, the State tells us the
situation here is not dangerous.

516
00:41:34,680 --> 00:41:37,220
Have faith, comrades.

517
00:41:38,850 --> 00:41:42,230
The State tells us it
wants to prevent a panic.

518
00:41:42,230 --> 00:41:44,440
Listen well.

519
00:41:47,060 --> 00:41:51,270
It's true, when the people see
the police, they will be afraid.

520
00:41:52,600 --> 00:41:54,730
But it is my experience

521
00:41:55,890 --> 00:41:58,060
that when the people ask questions

522
00:41:58,060 --> 00:42:01,430
that are not in their own best interest,

523
00:42:01,430 --> 00:42:03,430
they should simply be told

524
00:42:03,430 --> 00:42:05,600
to keep their minds on their labor

525
00:42:06,600 --> 00:42:11,470
and leave matters of
the State to the State.

526
00:42:13,140 --> 00:42:15,220
We seal off the city.

527
00:42:16,390 --> 00:42:18,060
No one leaves.

528
00:42:18,770 --> 00:42:20,970
And cut the phone lines.

529
00:42:20,970 --> 00:42:23,770
Contain the spread of misinformation.

530
00:42:26,430 --> 00:42:29,310
That is how we keep the people

531
00:42:29,310 --> 00:42:32,470
from undermining the
fruits of their own labor.

532
00:42:35,520 --> 00:42:37,310
Yes, comrades...

533
00:42:38,600 --> 00:42:42,640
we will all be rewarded
for what we do here tonight.

534
00:42:44,980 --> 00:42:49,480
This is our moment to shine.

535
00:42:54,270 --> 00:42:56,600
